<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="426" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1155,142,341]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,286,142,168]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović, 2022" authorityName="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović" authorityYear="2022" box="[302,590,143,168]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nymphaealis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[302,590,143,168]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Diaeretellus nymphaealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[604,700,143,168]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stary" authorityYear="1971" box="[845,976,143,168]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[845,976,143,168]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">D. palustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having 13- segmented antennae, and in parasitising 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1761" box="[631,787,178,203]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Rhopalosiphum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nymphaeae">
<emphasis box="[631,787,178,203]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">R. nymphaeae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can easily be differentiated from it by a more elongate pterostigma (ratio of length to width of pterostigma 4.80–5.00 in 
<taxonomicName authority="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović, 2022" authorityName="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović" authorityYear="2022" box="[191,361,247,272]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nymphaealis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[191,361,247,272]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">D. nymphaealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[371,463,247,272]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, while about 4.00 in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stary" authorityYear="1971" box="[708,832,247,272]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[708,832,247,272]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">D. palustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and a distinctly elongated flagellomere 11 (F11) – length/width ratio in 
<taxonomicName authority="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović, 2022" authorityName="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović" authorityYear="2022" box="[658,826,282,307]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nymphaealis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[658,826,282,307]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">D. nymphaealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[833,921,282,307]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
3.4, while about 
<quantity box="[1113,1155,282,307]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stary" authorityYear="1971" box="[160,281,316,341]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[160,281,316,341]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">D. palustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,401,1189]" box="[160,246,401,427]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,246,401,427]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,401,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis box="[160,217,436,461]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[230,321,436,461]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(a)). Eyes oval. Malar space equal to 0.4 longitudinal eye diameters. Clypeus oval with 5–6 long setae. Tentorial index (tentoriocular line/intertentorial line) about 0.5. Maxillary palps with 3 palpomeres, labial palps with 1 palpomere. Head width/mesoscutum width 1.3. Antennae 13-segmented, filiform, with semierect setae subequal to half of segment diameter (
<figureCitation box="[384,472,575,600]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,226,1228,1251]" captionTargetBox="[171,1145,150,1189]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[163,1153,142,1197]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov., female. (a) Antenna; (b) flagellomeres 1 and 2; (c) Flagellomere 11." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758529" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758529/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(a)). Flagellomere 1 (F1) and flagellomere 2 (F2) 2.5 (2.4–2.8) and 2 (1.9–2.1) times as long as wide, respectively; F1 sligthly longer than or equal to F2 (
<figureCitation box="[168,259,644,669]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,226,1228,1251]" captionTargetBox="[171,1145,150,1189]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[163,1153,142,1197]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov., female. (a) Antenna; (b) flagellomeres 1 and 2; (c) Flagellomere 11." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758529" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758529/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(b)). F1 without longitudinal placodes, F2 with 1–2. Flagellomere 11 (F11) very long, 3.5 times as long as wide, with 10–12 longitudinal placodes (
<figureCitation box="[910,998,679,704]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,226,1228,1251]" captionTargetBox="[171,1145,150,1189]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[163,1153,142,1197]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov., female. (a) Antenna; (b) flagellomeres 1 and 2; (c) Flagellomere 11." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758529" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758529/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(c)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,401,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<taxonomicName box="[192,308,714,739]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[192,308,714,739]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Mesosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Mesoscutum with incomplete notaulices, visible only in the very beginning of the anterior part, and with two longitudinal rows of setae along the dorsal surface (
<figureCitation box="[168,259,783,808]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(b)). Propodeum with a narrow central pentagonal areola (
<figureCitation box="[901,992,783,808]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(c)). Upper and lower areola with 4–7 and 0–2 setae, respectively. Fore wing pterostigma narrow and elongate, 4.9 (4.8–5.0) times as long as wide. Distal abscissa of R1 (= metacarpus) subequal to pterostigma length; pterostigma length/R1 length ratio 1.2 (1.1–1.3). Vein M+m-cu visible in some specimens, not visible in others (
<figureCitation box="[705,798,922,947]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(g)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,401,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis box="[192,306,956,981]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Metasoma</emphasis>
. Petiole 2.4 times as long as wide at spiracles, with 11–12 costulae on its anterolateral area and 1–2 long setae near the base on each side. Dorsal surface irregularly rugose (
<figureCitation box="[251,343,1026,1051]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(d)). Ovipositor sheath short, length/width ratio 1.7 (1.6–1.8) (
<figureCitation box="[1023,1114,1026,1051]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(e)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,401,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis box="[192,263,1060,1085]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Colour</emphasis>
. Head brown, mouthparts yellow. Antenna light brown, with a yellow ring at the base of F1. Mesoscutum and propodeum light brown to brown, legs and petiole light brown, metasoma and ovipositor sheaths brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,401,1189]" box="[192,426,1164,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis box="[192,322,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Body length</emphasis>
. 
<quantity box="[335,422,1164,1189]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1249,1725]" box="[160,218,1249,1275]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,218,1249,1275]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1249,1725]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis box="[160,217,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Head</emphasis>
. Eyes oval. Malar space equal to 0.36 longitudinal eye diameters. Clypeus oval with 5–6 setae. Tentorial index (tentoriocular line/intertentorial line) about 0.5. Maxillary palps with 3 palpomeres, labial palps with 1 palpomere. Head width/mesoscutum width 1.15. Antennae 16-segmented, filiform, with semierect setae subequal to half of segment diameter. Flagellomere 1 (F1) and flagellomere 2 (F2) 2.2 and 2 times as long as wide, respectively; F1 length equal to F2. F1 and F2 both with 5–6 longitudinal placodes. Flagellomere 11 (F11) very long, 3.4 times as long as wide, with 3–4 longitudinal placodes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1249,1725]" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">
<taxonomicName box="[192,308,1562,1587]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="2" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[192,308,1562,1587]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="425">Mesosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Mesoscutum with incomplete notaulices, visible only in the very beginning of the anterior part, and with two longitudinal rows of setae. Propodeum with a narrow central pentagonal areola. Fore wing pterostigma narrow and elongate, 5 times as long as wide. Distal abscissa of R1 (= metacarpus) subequal to pterostigma length; pterostigma length/R1 length ratio 1.1. Vein M+m-cu visible in some specimens.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758529" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6758529" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758529/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" startId="3.[160,226,1228,1251]" targetBox="[171,1145,150,1189]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1155,1228,1281]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,256,1228,1251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović, 2022" authorityName="Čkrkić &amp; Kocić &amp; Plećaš &amp; Petrović &amp; Tomanović" authorityYear="2022" box="[267,515,1228,1251]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Diaeretellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nymphaealis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[267,515,1228,1251]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Diaeretellus nymphaealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[526,611,1228,1251]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, female. (a) Antenna; (b) flagellomeres 1 and 2; (c) Flagellomere 11.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1155,1380,1543]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[192,306,1380,1405]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Metasoma</emphasis>
. Petiole with 11–12 costulae on its anterolateral area. Dorsal surface irregularly rugose. Genitalia shown in 
<figureCitation box="[521,614,1414,1439]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1401,1424]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,145,1330]" captionTargetId="figure-58@4.[163,1153,142,1369]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Diaeretellus nymphaealis sp. nov. Female: (a) head; (b) mesoscutum; (c) propodeum; (d) petiole; (e) ovipositor sheaths; (g) fore wing. (f) Male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758533/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(f).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1155,1380,1543]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[192,263,1449,1474]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Colour</emphasis>
. Head brown, mouthparts yellow. Antenna light brown. Mesoscutum and propodeum light brown to brown, legs and petiole light brown, metasoma brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1155,1380,1543]" box="[192,407,1518,1543]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis box="[192,322,1518,1543]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Body length</emphasis>
. 
<quantity box="[335,403,1518,1543]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="429" pageId="3" pageNumber="426" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1156,1603,1629]" box="[160,1156,1603,1629]" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,291,1603,1629]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="426">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new species is derived from the host plant and host aphid.
</paragraph>
